<br>
#Rulesets
<br>
DnD has been around a long time, and people have played with many different versions of the rules.
Here are the major rulesets. Check whichever ones seem interesting to you.
<br>
<div class="field">
  <br>
  The Original edition of Dungeons and Dragons was released in 1974 by Gary Gygax and David Arneson.
  <%= f.label(:original_ruleset)%>
  <%= f.check_box :original_ruleset %>
  <br>
  The Advanced edition of Dungeons and Dragons was released between 1977 and 1979 and codified in three rulebooks:
  <%= f.label :advanced_ruleset %>
  <%= f.check_box :advanced_ruleset %>
  <br>
  3rd Edition was initially released in 2000 as a revision of the Advanced ruleset,
  <%= f.label :third %>
  <%= f.check_box :third %>
  <br>
  Dungeons and Dragons 3.5 edition was a small update to the 3rd edition, which boils down to a few tweaks to spells, monsters, and
  feats.
  <%= f.label :three_point_five %>
  <%= f.check_box :three_point_five %>
  <br>
  Pathfinder was a game released as sort of an expansion to v3 and v3.5 of Dungeons and Dragons. Sometimes called "v3.75", Pathfinder
  expanded on the rules and mechanics of version 3 with some slight changes to mechanics like skills and spells.
  <%= f.label :pathfinder %>
  <%= f.check_box :pathfinder %>
  <br>
  The 4th Edition of Dungeons and Dragons introduced some pretty significant changes to DnD mechanics.
  <%= f.label :fourth %>
  <%= f.check_box :fourth %>
  <br>
  In contrast with 4th edition, skills took a backseat to the main abilities.
  <%= f.label :fifth %>
  <%= f.check_box :fifth %>
  <br>
  Homebrew refers to the various "house" rules that players use. With such a creative game, players and DMs modify rules for optimal enjoyment. Choose this for a more flexible game experience.
  <%= f.label :homebrew %>
  <%= f.check_box :homebrew %>
  </div>
